    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Offshore Wind Plan: A Long Time Coming</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Long Island Power Authority chairman Richard Kessel letter on David Bishop and William Lauder's March 12 Op-Ed article holds offshore wind project is part of LIPA's energy master plan</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The offshore wind project is not a whim. It's part of the Long Island Power Authority's energy master plan.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The offshore wind project is not a whim. It's part of the Long Island Power Authority's energy master plan.</p>
        <p>The project will receive extensive review by more than a dozen entities, including the Minerals Management Service of the United States Interior Department, which now has lead federal review authority. A full environmental impact statement will be done.</p>
        <p>Europe is using more wind power, and it's the fastest growing alternative energy resource in the United States. Using tax credits will lower the power cost.</p>
        <p>The Winergy proposal is interesting, but the Plum Island area does not have sustained winds similar to Long Island's South Shore.</p>
        <p>Western Suffolk and Nassau counties have the highest electric demand. FPL Energy will be responsible for maintenance and repair of the turbines.</p>
        <p>The view is the primary opposition to the project. I love the view, too. But the larger issue is: How to secure Long Island's energy future against the ever-increasing cost of fossil fuels, since about 98 percent of our on-island electric supply comes from these fuels?</p>
        <p>We failed to act nationally and locally over 30 years ago. We can't afford to fail again.</p>
        <p>Richard M. Kessel  Uniondale</p>
        <p>The writer is chairman, Long Island Power Authority.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
